         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0504">
               <p>Crook was converted at a Methodist service in <date when="1770">1770</date> and
                  became an active lay member. In late <date when="1774">1774</date> the society in
                     <placeName>Liverpool</placeName> convinced Crook to travel to <placeName>Isle
                     of Man</placeName> and attempt to launch a Methodist presence there. His
                  efforts met with some success, and confirmed in Crook a call to <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg> ministry. He was admitted on trial at
                  Conference in <date when="1775-08">August 1775</date> (see <hi rend="italic"
                     >Works</hi>, 10:440) and assigned to <placeName>Lincolnshire West</placeName>.
                  He would serve for a quarter of a century. See his biography in <hi rend="italic"
                     >MM</hi> 31 (<date when="1808">1808</date>): 3–10, 49–57, 97–105, 145–51,
                  193–202; and <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley, <date when="1806"
                     >1806</date>), 2:323–24.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
